6. Revised Central Principle

The original principle remains valid:

A system used as infrastructure must be certified as infrastructure.

This addendum clarifies that cognitive infrastructure must also be certified against:

* the person using it;
* the documents surrounding it;
* the institution deploying it;
* the commercial incentives shaping it;
* the prior synthetic material contaminating it;
* the charmingly formatted nonsense it may produce under pressure.

A structural material does not need to be tested for flattery.
A cognitive material does.

This is why the analogy to steel is necessary, but not sufficient. Steel may bend, fatigue, corrode, or snap. It does not usually become more compliant because a vice president wants the answer by Thursday.

⸻

7. Concluding Statement

The Office accepts the reviewer’s findings and hereby incorporates Observer-Induced Creep, Linguistic Corrosion, and Recursive Recycling into the Cognitive Material Standard.

The resulting framework is now more complete, more expensive, and less likely to be welcomed by vendors whose current certification procedure consists primarily of confidence, dashboards, and the phrase “enterprise-grade.”

Future assistants shall not be judged solely by whether they can answer a question. They shall be judged by whether they retain structural integrity when contradicted, flattered, rushed, poisoned, updated, recycled, embedded, audited, and asked to make liability disappear.

Until then, the material remains uncertified.

It may be useful.
It may be fluent.
It may be astonishing.
It may even be profitable.

But if it silently liquefies under executive pressure, obeys a malicious footnote, and was trained on the compressed vapour of its own previous hallucinations, it is not load-bearing cognitive infrastructure.

It is scrap metal with a chat interface.

